   <abstract xlink:href="http://lib.lsu.edu/services/oralhistory/abstracts/university/distinguished_faculty/Griffith_Ordell_T654-T658_T687_T759.abs.pdf">Griffith discusses life in Baton Rouge in the early twentieth century and Louisiana
            State University between the 1930s and 1980s. She discusses the design and buildings of
            the LSU campus; several administrators, faculty members, and employees; admissions
            procedures; the enrollment of foreign students; racial integration; and student
            behavior. Griffith discusses admissions procedures at LSU and the handling of transfer
            credits and credits from unaccredited or foreign universities. She talks about conflicts
            with faculty, administrators and coaches over the admittance of students. She recounts
            her experiences with various faculty and administrators during her many years at LSU
            including John Hunter, Martin Woodin, Charles Coates, Albert Clary, Arthur Choppin,
            General Troy Middleton, Carl Maddox and others.</abstract>
